Norwegian authorities authorized the oil company Statoil to partially resume production on two North Sea oil platforms that were shut down in late November because of a gas leak.
The green light from the Petroleum Safety Authority will enable Statoil to produce up to 100,000 barrels of oil a day in an initial phase, compared to 205,000 bpd before the accident.
The shutdown resulted in a roughly 6.4 percent reduction in the 3.2 million barrel per day production capacity that makes Norway the world's third-largest oil exporter, after Saudi Arabia and Russia.
